# Discord Bot

Connect a Discord application so people can run `/bg` and receive alerts in Discord. This
page covers the Discord-specific steps; for account linking, alert delivery, and the Admin
UI / environment-variable workflow that all platforms share, see
[Chat Bots](/docs/bots).

## 1. Create a Discord application

1. Go to the [Discord Developer Portal](https://discord.com/developers/applications) and
   click **New Application**.
2. Give it a name (e.g. *Nocturne*) and create it.

## 2. Collect the credentials

From the application you just created:

| Field | Where to find it |
|-------|------------------|
| **Application ID** | **General Information** tab |
| **Public Key** | **General Information** tab |
| **Bot Token** | **Bot** tab — click **Reset Token** and copy the value |

<Callout type="warning" title="Save the bot token now">
  Discord shows the bot token only once when it's generated. If you lose it, reset it again
  on the <strong>Bot</strong> tab — note that resetting invalidates the previous token.
</Callout>

## 3. Configure Nocturne

Enter the three values using either method (see [Chat Bots](/docs/bots) for the full workflow).

### Option A: Admin UI

At **Settings > Admin > Integrations**, fill in the **Discord** card:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| **Bot Token** | The bot token from step 2 |
| **Public Key** | The public key from step 2 |
| **Application ID** | The application ID from step 2 |

Turn **Enabled** on, click **Save**, and restart the Nocturne web service.

### Option B: Environment variables

```bash
DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=...
DISCORD_PUBLIC_KEY=...
DISCORD_APPLICATION_ID=...
```

Then restart Nocturne.

## 4. Set the interactions endpoint

1. In the Developer Portal, open **General Information**.
2. Set **Interactions Endpoint URL** to:

   ```
   https://your-instance.com/api/v4/webhooks/discord
   ```

3. Save.

When you save, Discord sends a signed test request that Nocturne verifies with your **Public
Key**. Discord rejects the URL if verification fails.

<Callout type="info" title="Order matters">
  Configure the credentials in Nocturne (step 3) and restart <em>before</em> saving the
  interactions endpoint URL. The verification request only passes once Nocturne has the
  public key loaded.
</Callout>

## 5. Register the slash commands

Slash commands (`/bg`, `/glucose`, `/connect`, `/disconnect`, `/status`) are registered with
Discord once, as a deploy step — not at app startup. Run:

```bash
DISCORD_APPLICATION_ID=... DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=... \
  pnpm --filter @nocturne/bot bot:register-discord-commands
```

This bulk-overwrites the application's global commands to match Nocturne's manifest.

<Callout type="tip" title="Global commands take time to appear">
  Newly registered global commands can take up to an hour to propagate across Discord. They
  show up in servers and DMs once Discord has distributed them.
</Callout>

## 6. Invite the bot to a server

To use `/bg` inside a Discord server (DMs work without this), invite the bot with the
`bot` and `applications.commands` scopes. The quickest path: as a linked user, open
**Settings > Integrations > Discord** in Nocturne and use **Open Discord invite**, which
builds the correct OAuth2 URL for you.

## 7. Account linking from the web (optional)

Users can always link by running `/connect` in Discord. If you also want the in-app **Link
my Discord account** button (**Settings > Integrations > Discord**), enable Discord OAuth2:

1. In the Developer Portal, open **OAuth2** and copy the **Client Secret**.
2. Add this redirect URL under **OAuth2 > Redirects**:

   ```
   https://your-instance.com/auth/bot/discord/callback
   ```

   Use your root domain (`BASE_DOMAIN`), not a tenant subdomain.
3. Give the client secret to Nocturne, either:
   - **Admin UI** — enter it in the **Client Secret** field on the Discord card at
     **Settings > Admin > Integrations** (the same card as the bot credentials), or
   - **Environment** — set `DISCORD_CLIENT_SECRET` and restart Nocturne.

   The **Application ID** (`DISCORD_APPLICATION_ID`) doubles as the OAuth2 client ID, so no
   separate client ID is needed.

Without a client secret, the in-app button is hidden and linking is done with `/connect`.

## 8. Test it

1. In a server the bot is in (or a DM), run `/connect` and complete the link.
2. Run `/bg` and confirm the latest reading comes back.
